  "prompt": "Why mobile phone is also know as cell phone?",
  "response": "The term \"cell phone\" comes from the way mobile phone networks are structured. Mobile phones connect to a network of fixed-location base stations, which cover specific areas known as \"cells.\" Each cell has its own base station that communicates with the mobile devices within that area. \n\nThis cellular structure allows for efficient use of the available radio spectrum and enables many users to share the same frequency bands by reusing the frequencies in different cells that are spaced far enough apart. As users move from one cell to another, their calls can be seamlessly handed off from one base station to another, allowing for continuous service.\n\nThus, the name \"cell phone\" reflects the use of this cellular network architecture, while \"mobile phone\" emphasizes the portability and mobility aspect of these devices. Both terms are widely used and are often interchangeable, but \"cell phone\" specifically highlights the technology behind the service.",
